9
00:00:35,140 --> 00:00:35,970
What is a Virus?

10
00:00:37,170 --> 00:00:40,030
A Virus is defined as a small infectious
agent.

11
00:00:40,030 --> 00:00:41,980
It is Submicroscopic.

12
00:00:41,980 --> 00:00:45,420
It is not a living organism in contrast to
bacteria.

13
00:00:45,420 --> 00:00:47,770
And it does not have ribosomes.

14
00:00:47,770 --> 00:00:50,590
A Virus is an obligate intracellular
parasite.

15
00:00:50,590 --> 00:00:54,369
It is completely dependent on a living
host cell for reproduction.

16
00:00:57,840 --> 00:01:00,390
The infectious virus particle is called a
Virion and

17
00:01:00,390 --> 00:01:03,070
is composed of a limited number of
structures.

18
00:01:03,070 --> 00:01:06,960
The Capsid is a protein coat that protects
the nucleic acid genome.

19
00:01:06,960 --> 00:01:09,849
The Capsid can also be used for attachment
to a host cell.

20
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:15,740
The Envelope is found only in some viruses
and

21
00:01:15,740 --> 00:01:19,510
consists of a Lipid membrane derived from
host cell membrane.

22
00:01:19,510 --> 00:01:22,090
The envelope functions as an extra
protective layer.

23
00:01:23,770 --> 00:01:27,490
Glycoproteins are anchored in the envelope
and are used by the virus for

24
00:01:27,490 --> 00:01:29,010
attachment to a host cell.

25
00:01:32,190 --> 00:01:34,550
The origin of viruses is debated.

26
00:01:34,550 --> 00:01:39,040
Theories include one, that viruses were
once just Genetic elements that

27
00:01:39,040 --> 00:01:42,000
gained the ability to exit one cell and
enter another.

28
00:01:43,120 --> 00:01:47,370
Two, viruses transformed from a free
living organism into a parasite.

29
00:01:49,030 --> 00:01:51,379
Could viruses be the Precursor of life?

30
00:01:52,440 --> 00:01:55,190
Viruses are not a living organism.

31
00:01:55,190 --> 00:01:58,950
They are not part of the tree of life, as
you can see in the image.

32
00:01:58,950 --> 00:02:03,900
However, viruses infect all living things,
including Bacteria, Fungi, and Animals.

33
00:02:05,620 --> 00:02:08,030
In fact, viruses are part of us.

34
00:02:08,030 --> 00:02:11,590
Each bacteria in our intestines can be a
home for a virus.

35
00:02:11,590 --> 00:02:15,140
And a portion of our DNA, comes from
endogenous retroviruses.

36
00:02:17,300 --> 00:02:20,060
Viruses have evolved and will continue to
evolve.

37
00:02:20,060 --> 00:02:22,440
Emerging viruses, prove this point.

38
00:02:22,440 --> 00:02:25,510
Most of the recent, new emerging viruses
are zoonotic.

39
00:02:25,510 --> 00:02:30,750
The viruses is transmitted from animal to
man, either directly or via a vector.

40
00:02:30,750 --> 00:02:32,800
The animal serves as a reservoir, and

41
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:36,810
wild animals, wildlife, are increasingly
implicated in zoonoses.

42
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:41,560
New viral infections on humans evolve
based on two concepts.

43
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:46,770
One New viruses arise from mutations,
reassortment, or recombinations.

44
00:02:46,770 --> 00:02:50,590
These new viruses attempt to achieve
successful replication within old and

45
00:02:50,590 --> 00:02:51,360
new host.

46
00:02:52,390 --> 00:02:57,605
Two, New environments develop that place
humans in closer contact to animals.

47
00:02:57,605 --> 00:03:02,554
Ecology changes and an increase in world
travel can create these new environments.

